  "stimulus": "Let $f$ be the function defined by\n$$f(x) = \\begin{cases} 1 - 2\\sin x & \\text{if } x \\le 0 \\\\ e^{-4x} & \\text{if } x > 0 \\end{cases}$$",
  "stimulus_image": null,
  "documents": null,
  "parts": [
    {
      "letter": "a",
      "prompt": "Show that $f$ is continuous at $x = 0$.",
      "point_value": 2,
      "scoring_notes": "From scoring key: $\\lim_{x \\to 0^-}(1-2\\sin x) = 1$, $\\lim_{x \\to 0^+} e^{-4x} = 1$, and $f(0) = 1$. All three equal, so $f$ is continuous at $x=0$.",
      "requires_drawing": false,
      "reference_image": null,
      "scoring_points": [
        {
          "point_id": "a1",
          "point_value": 1,
          "description": "Shows both one-sided limits equal 1",
          "alternatives": [
            {
              "required_elements": [
                "Shows both one-sided limits equal 1"
              ],
              "correct_example": "$\\lim_{x \\to 0^-} f(x) = 1 - 2\\sin(0) = 1$ and $\\lim_{x \\to 0^+} f(x) = e^0 = 1$"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "point_id": "a2",
          "point_value": 1,
          "description": "Correct conclusion: since $f(0) = 1 - 2\\sin(0) = 1$ and $\\lim_{x \\to 0} f(x) = 1 = f(0)$, $f$ is continuous at $x = 0$",
          "alternatives": [
            {
              "required_elements": [
                "Correct conclusion: since $f(0) = 1 - 2\\sin(0) = 1$",
                "$\\lim_{x \\to 0} f(x) = 1 = f(0)$, $f$ is continuous at $x = 0$"
              ]
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "letter": "b",
      "prompt": "Find $f'(x)$ for $x < 0$ and find $f'(x)$ for $x > 0$. Determine whether $f$ has a local minimum, local maximum, or neither at each of the $x$-values for which $f'(x) = -3$.",
      "point_value": 3,
      "scoring_notes": "From scoring key: $f'(x) = -3$ only at $x = \\frac{1}{4}\\ln\\frac{4}{3}$ (in $(0,\\infty)$). $f'$ does not change sign there (remains negative), so $f$ has neither a local minimum nor a local maximum.",
      "requires_drawing": false,
      "reference_image": null,
      "scoring_points": [
        {
          "point_id": "b1",
          "point_value": 1,
          "description": "Correct piecewise derivative",
          "alternatives": [
            {
              "required_elements": [
                "Correct piecewise derivative"
              ],
              "correct_example": "$f'(x) = \\begin{cases} -2\\cos x & x < 0 \\\\ -4e^{-4x} & x > 0 \\end{cases}$"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "point_id": "b2",
          "point_value": 1,
          "description": "Correct solution: for $x < 0$",
          "alternatives": [
            {
              "required_elements": [
                "Correct solution: for $x < 0$"
              ],
              "correct_example": "$-2\\cos x = -3 \\Rightarrow \\cos x = \\frac{3}{2}$, which has no solution; for $x > 0$: $-4e^{-4x} = -3 \\Rightarrow e^{-4x} = \\frac{3}{4} \\Rightarrow x = -\\frac{1}{4}\\ln\\frac{3}{4} = \\frac{1}{4}\\ln\\frac{4}{3}$"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "point_id": "b3",
          "point_value": 1,
          "description": "Correct conclusion",
          "alternatives": [
            {
              "required_elements": [
                "Correct conclusion"
              ],
              "correct_example": "$f'(x) < -3$ for $0 < x < \\frac{1}{4}\\ln\\frac{4}{3}$ and $f'(x) > -3$ for $x > \\frac{1}{4}\\ln\\frac{4}{3}$; $f'$ changes from more negative to less negative (increasing through $-3$), so $f$ has neither a local min nor a local max at $x = \\frac{1}{4}\\ln\\frac{4}{3}$"
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "letter": "c",
      "prompt": "Find the average value of $f$ on the interval $-1 \\le x \\le 1$.",
      "point_value": 4,
      "scoring_notes": "From scoring key: Average value $= \\frac{1}{2}\\int_{-1}^{1} f(x)\\, dx = \\frac{1}{2}\\left[(x+2\\cos x)\\big|_{-1}^{0} + \\left(-\\frac{1}{4}e^{-4x}\\right)\\big|_{0}^{1}\\right] = \\frac{1}{2}\\left(3 - 2\\cos 1 + \\frac{1}{4} - \\frac{1}{4e^4}\\right) = \\frac{13}{8} - \\cos 1 - \\frac{1}{8e^4}$.",
      "requires_drawing": false,
      "reference_image": null,
      "scoring_points": [
        {
          "point_id": "c1",
          "point_value": 1,
          "description": "Correct setup",
          "alternatives": [
            {
              "required_elements": [
                "Correct setup"
              ],
              "correct_example": "$\\frac{1}{2}\\int_{-1}^{1} f(x)\\, dx = \\frac{1}{2}\\left[\\int_{-1}^{0}(1 - 2\\sin x)\\, dx + \\int_{0}^{1} e^{-4x}\\, dx\\right]$"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "point_id": "c2",
          "point_value": 1,
          "description": "Correct antiderivative for left piece",
          "alternatives": [
            {
              "required_elements": [
                "Correct antiderivative for left piece"
              ],
              "correct_example": "$\\left[x + 2\\cos x\\right]_{-1}^{0} = (0 + 2) - (-1 + 2\\cos(-1)) = 3 - 2\\cos(1)$"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "point_id": "c3",
          "point_value": 1,
          "description": "Correct antiderivative for right piece",
          "alternatives": [
            {
              "required_elements": [
                "Correct antiderivative for right piece"
              ],
              "correct_example": "$\\left[-\\frac{1}{4}e^{-4x}\\right]_{0}^{1} = -\\frac{1}{4}e^{-4} + \\frac{1}{4}$"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "point_id": "c4",
          "point_value": 1,
          "description": "Correct answer",
          "alternatives": [
            {
              "required_elements": [
                "Correct answer"
              ],
              "correct_example": "$\\frac{1}{2}\\left(3 - 2\\cos 1 + \\frac{1}{4} - \\frac{1}{4e^4}\\right) = \\frac{13}{8} - \\cos 1 - \\frac{1}{8e^4}$"
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
